response:
 Here we have $y=|x|$ and $g(x)=-x^2+\frac{35}{4}=\frac{35}{4}-x^2$. So we have $-x^2+\frac{35}{4}\ge|x|$ $\Rightarrow$ $x\in[-\frac{5}{2},\frac{5}{2}]$ $\Rightarrow$ $g(x)\ge0\Rightarrow x\in[-\frac{5}{2},\frac{5}{2}]$. Moreover, if $x\in[-\frac{5}{2},\frac{5}{2}]$, then $0\ge-x^2+\frac{35}{4}\ge|x|$, i.e., $x\in[-\frac{5}{2},\frac{5}{2}]$. Therefore, the area we need to find is the area enclosed by these curves. Our key idea is that the area we need to find is the area between the two curves plus the area of the two triangles at the two points of intersection. The equation $-x^2=\frac{35}{4}$ has no solution, while the equation $-x^2+|x|-\frac{35}{4}=0$ has at least one real solution: $|x|=\frac{\pm1\pm\sqrt{141}}{8}$, is 
\[F(\frac{5}{2})-F(-\frac{5}{2})+\frac{1}{2}[-\frac{5}{2},\frac{5}{2}]-2F(\frac{5}{2}),\] 
where $F(x)=F_2(x)-F_1(x)$ is the area of the curve $y=x^2$ bounded by $y=|x|$ and $y=g(x)$ from $x=a$ to $x=b$.
;<answer> 
\begin{align*}
&F(x) \\
&= \int_{\frac{-5}{2}}^{\frac{5}{2}}(-x^2+\frac{35}{4})-|x| \space dx \\
&= -\frac{1}{3}x^3+\frac{35}{4}x-\frac{1}{2}x^2 \\
&= \frac{25}{6}
\end{align*}
Area= \begin{align*}
&F(\frac{5}{2})-F(-\frac{5}{2})+\frac{1}{2}[-\frac{5}{2},\frac{5}{2}]-2F(\frac{5}{2}) \\
&= \frac{25}{6}+F(-\frac{5}{2}) \\
&=\frac{25}{6}+\frac{1}{2}(-(\frac{5}{2})^3-\frac{1}{2}(\frac{5}{2})^2+\frac{35}{4}\frac{5}{2})-2\frac{25}{6}=-\frac{55}{24}
\end{align*}
The area of the triangles is $\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{5}{2}\cdot\frac{5}{4}+\frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{5}{2}\cdot\frac{7}{4}=\frac{45}{16}$.
Final area is $-\frac{55}{24}+\frac{45}{16}=\boxed{\frac{25}{48}}$.
</answer>

